#: ../../../installing.rst:-1
msgid ""
"Learn how Spack installs packages: the interactive terminal UI, parallelism "
"via a POSIX jobserver, multi-process installs, background execution, and "
"handling build failures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:15
msgid "Installing Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:17
msgid ""
"This page covers the ``spack install`` experience in detail, including the "
"interactive terminal UI (TUI), parallelism, background execution, and "
"handling build failures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:19
msgid ""
"Before diving in, ensure you are familiar with :doc:`package_fundamentals` "
"for basic usage and spec syntax."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:21
msgid ""
"The TUI and POSIX jobserver are new in Spack 1.2 and require a Unix-like "
"platform."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:26
msgid "Interactive terminal UI"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:28
msgid ""
"By default, ``spack install`` shows live progress inline in the terminal. "
"Completed packages scroll into terminal history, while active builds update "
"dynamically below the progress header."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:31
msgid "Every package in the install plan is shown with its current status:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:33
msgid ""
"$ spack install -j16 python\n"
"[+] abc1234 zlib@1.3.1 /home/user/spack/opt/spack/... (4s)\n"
"[+] def5678 pkgconf@2.2.0 /home/user/spack/opt/spack/... (6s)\n"
"[+] 9ab0123 ncurses@6.5 /home/user/spack/opt/spack/... (23s)\n"
"Progress: 3/7  +/-: 4 jobs  /: filter  v: logs  n/p: next/prev\n"
"[/] cde4567 readline@8.2 configure (11s)\n"
"[/] fgh8901 openssl@3.4.1 build (18s)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:43
msgid "Status indicators:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:45
msgid "``[+]`` finished successfully"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:46
msgid "``[x]`` failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:47
msgid "``[/]``, ``[-]``, ``[\\]``, ``[|]`` building (rotating spinner)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:48
msgid "``[e]`` external"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:50
msgid ""
"**Log-following mode**: press ``v`` to switch from the overview to a live "
"view of build output. Press ``v``, ``q``, or ``Esc`` to return to the "
"overview."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:53
msgid ""
"While in log-following mode, press ``n`` / ``p`` to cycle to the next or "
"previous build. Press ``/``, type a pattern, and press ``Enter`` to jump to "
"a matching build (``Esc`` cancels the filter)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:56
msgid ""
"When a build fails, press ``v`` to see a parsed error summary and the path "
"to the full log."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:60
msgid "Parallelism"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:62
msgid ""
"Spack controls parallelism at two levels: the number of build jobs shared "
"across all packages (``-j``), and the number of packages building "
"concurrently (``-p``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:65
msgid "Build-level parallelism (``-j``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:67
msgid ""
"The ``-j`` flag controls the **total** number of concurrent build jobs via a "
"POSIX jobserver. All build processes (``make``, ``cmake``, ``ninja``, etc.) "
"share the same jobserver, so ``-j16`` means at most 16 build jobs across "
"*all* packages combined. This is the primary concurrency knob."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:71
msgid "$ spack install -j16 python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:75
msgid ""
"Spack creates a POSIX jobserver compatible with GNU Make's jobserver "
"protocol. Child build systems automatically respect it through "
"``MAKEFLAGS``, so total CPU usage stays bounded regardless of how many "
"packages are building concurrently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:80
msgid ""
"If an external jobserver is already present in ``MAKEFLAGS``, for example "
"when Spack itself is invoked from inside a larger ``make`` build, Spack "
"attaches to the existing jobserver instead of creating its own."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:83
msgid "Package-level parallelism (``-p``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:85
msgid ""
"The ``-p`` / ``--concurrent-packages`` flag limits how many packages can be "
"in the build queue simultaneously. By default there is no limit, and "
"packages are started as jobserver tokens become available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:88
msgid "$ spack install -j16 -p4 python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:92
msgid ""
"This builds with 16 total make-jobs but never more than 4 packages at once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:95
msgid "Dynamic adjustment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:97
msgid "You can adjust parallelism while a build is running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:99
msgid "Press ``+`` to add a job (increases ``-j`` by 1)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:100
msgid "Press ``-`` to remove a job (decreases ``-j`` by 1)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:102
msgid ""
"When reducing parallelism, Spack waits for currently running jobs to finish "
"before the new limit takes effect; it does not kill active processes. The "
"progress header shows the adjustment in progress, e.g. ``+/-: 4=>2 jobs``, "
"until the actual count reaches the target."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:107
msgid "Multi-process and multi-node installs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:109
msgid ""
"Multiple ``spack install`` processes can safely run concurrently, whether on "
"the same machine or across multiple nodes in a cluster with a shared "
"filesystem. Spack coordinates through :ref:`per-prefix filesystem locks "
"<filesystem-requirements>`: before building a package, the process acquires "
"an exclusive lock on its install prefix. If another process already holds "
"the lock, Spack waits rather than building a second copy. When a process "
"encounters a prefix that was already installed, it simply skips it and moves "
"on to the next install."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:114
msgid ""
"For best results on a cluster, it's recommended to limit per-process package-"
"level parallelism (e.g., ``spack install -p2``) for better load balancing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:118
msgid "Non-interactive mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:120
msgid ""
"When the controlling process is not a tty, such as in CI pipelines, when "
"redirecting output to a file, or when running in the background, Spack skips "
"the TUI and prints simple line-based status updates instead. Use ``spack "
"install -v`` to also print build output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:123
msgid "You can also background builds:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:125
msgid ""
"**Suspend and resume**: press ``Ctrl-Z`` to suspend the install, then ``bg`` "
"to let it continue in the background or ``fg`` to bring it back. Child "
"builds are paused while suspended, and resumed when continued in the "
"background or foreground. The TUI is suppressed while backgrounded and "
"restored on ``fg``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:128
msgid ""
"**Start in the background**: run ``spack install ... &`` to skip the TUI "
"entirely and build in the background from the start."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:132
msgid ""
"You don't need a new terminal or SSH session to keep a build running — just "
"suspend it with ``Ctrl-Z`` and ``bg``, then continue working."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:136
msgid "Handling failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:138
msgid ""
"By default, Spack continues building other packages when one fails (best-"
"effort). Use ``--fail-fast`` to stop immediately on the first failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:141
msgid "$ spack install --fail-fast python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:145
msgid ""
"Failed builds show ``[x]`` in the overview. Navigate to a failed build and "
"press ``v`` to see a parsed error summary and the path to the full log."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:148
msgid ""
"See :ref:`spack install <spack-install>` for the full set of flags related "
"to debugging and controlling build behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:152
msgid "Build isolation and sandboxing (Linux)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:154
msgid ""
"Spack can run builds in an unprivileged sandbox to restrict filesystem and "
"network access. This opt-in feature requires Linux 5.13+ with Landlock "
"support (network restrictions require Linux 6.7+). Sandboxing is meant for "
"build reproducibility and bug containment rather than acting as a strict "
"security boundary, as package recipes still execute outside the sandbox "
"ahead of the build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:158
msgid ""
"When enabled, the stage directory, install prefix, system temp directory and "
"``/dev/null`` are implicitly writable. Spack-installed dependencies "
"(excluding externals) are implicitly readable. All other paths must be "
"explicitly allowed in configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:162
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  sandbox:\n"
"    enable: true          # Enable for all builds\n"
"    allow_network: false  # Disable TCP network access during the build "
"phase\n"
"    allow_read:           # Additional paths with read and execute "
"permissions\n"
"    - /usr\n"
"    allow_write:          # Additional paths with write and execute "
"permissions\n"
"    - /scratch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:173
msgid ""
"The sandbox activates immediately after source extraction and prefix "
"creation. Note that network restrictions only apply during the build phases, "
"leaving Spack's own fetch operations unaffected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:176
msgid ""
"File system restrictions are complementary to existing file permissions and "
"ACLs; they cannot grant access to files the user does not already have "
"permission to read or write."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../installing.rst:178
msgid ""
"Spack's sandboxing complements external containerization tools like Podman "
"or Bubblewrap: while a container must grant the main Spack process write "
"access to the entire software store, Landlock dynamically confines each "
"build subprocess strictly to its exact, package-specific install prefix."
msgstr ""
